| ‚ùì **Question**                                                 | üí¨ **Answer**                                                                         |
| -------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Q1. What is the N-Queen problem?                               | It is to place N queens on an N√óN chessboard so that no two queens attack each other. |
| Q2. What technique is used here?                               | Backtracking (a type of recursive algorithm).                                         |
| Q3. What does ‚Äúbacktracking‚Äù mean?                             | Trying all possibilities, and undoing (backtracking) when a partial solution fails.   |
| Q4. Why are we using sets for columns and diagonals?           | To efficiently check if a queen‚Äôs position is under attack in O(1) time.              |
| Q5. What is the base condition of recursion?                   | When all queens are successfully placed (`r == n`).                                   |
| Q6. How many possible configurations are there for N-Queens?   | It depends on N; for example, 4-Queens has 2 solutions, 8-Queens has 92.              |
| Q7. What is the time complexity?                               | O(N!).                                                                                |
| Q8. How do we represent the board?                             | As a 2D matrix using lists in Python.                                                 |
| Q9. What is the purpose of `posDiag` and `negDiag`?            | To check diagonal attacks (`r+c` and `r-c`).                                          |
| Q10. What happens when no valid position is found for a queen? | The algorithm backtracks and tries a different column in the previous row.            |




| Concept            | Explanation                                 |
| ------------------ | ------------------------------------------- |
| Problem Type       | Constraint satisfaction problem             |
| Approach           | Backtracking                                |
| Representation     | Matrix (2D list)                            |
| Conditions Checked | No two queens share same column or diagonal |
| Fixed Condition    | First queen is already placed               |
| Goal               | Generate all safe configurations            |
| Use Case           | AI, chess, constraint solvers               |




| Type     | Complexity | Explanation                                                |
| -------- | ---------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| ‚è±Ô∏è Time  | **O(N!)**  | Because every queen placement leads to recursive branching |
| üíæ Space | **O(N¬≤)**  | For the board and recursion stack                          |
